      <hr color=#990000>
      </div></td>
</tr>

<!-- this is the content table -->

<tr><td valign="top"><div>

<font size="+4" color=#990000>An indirect object</font> receives the action of the verb indirectly:<br>



<table align="center" cellpadding=5 bgcolor="#E0F0F5" width="850">
<tr>
<td><div>She buys chocolates <font color="#3915B4"><strong>for me</strong></font>.<br>
She buys chocolates <font color="#3915B4"><strong>for you</strong></font>.<br>
She buys chocolates <font color="#3915B4"><strong>for him / her / it</strong></font>.<br>
She buys chocolates <font color="#3915B4"><strong>for us</strong></font>.<br>
She buys chocolates <font color="#3915B4"><strong>for you (all)</strong></font>.<br>
She buys chocolates <font color="#3915B4"><strong>for them</strong></font>.<br>
</div></td>
</tr>
</table>
<br>
Note how "chocolates" is the direct object, and the "me, you, him..." receive the action of the 
verb <strong>indirectly</strong>. That's what makes them 
indirect object pronouns.<br>
<br>
<font size="+4" color=#990000>In Spanish</font> the direct object pronouns are:<br>


<table align="center" cellpadding=5 bgcolor="#E0F0F5" width="850">
<tr>
<td width=50%><div>Ella <font color="#3915B4"><strong>me</strong></font> compra chocolates.<br>
Ella <font color="#3915B4"><strong>te</strong></font> compra chocolates.<br>
Ella <font color="#990000"><strong>le </strong></font>compra chocolates.<br>
Ella <font color="#3915B4"><strong>nos</strong></font> compra chocolates.<br>
Ella <font color="#3915B4"><strong>os</strong></font> compra chocolates. <br>
Ella <font color="#990000"><strong>les</strong></font> compra chocolates.<br>
</div></td>

<td><div>
(for "yo")<br>
(for "t&uacute;")<br>
(for "usted, &eacute;l, ella")<br>
(for "nosotros, nosotras")<br>
(for "vosotros")<br>
(for "ustedes, ellos, ellas")<br>
</div></td>
</tr>
</table>
<br>
Note that they look like direct object pronouns, with the exception of "<font color="#990000">le</font>" and "<font color="#990000">les</font>".
</div></td></tr>







